<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-876-028  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 876 028.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  Oct 1989 v22 n10 p53(13).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Graphical configuration programming: the structural description,construction and evolution of software systems using graphics.andO;(Visualization in Computing) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kramer, Jeff; Magee, Jeff; Ng, Keng.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Configuration programming is defined as programming at theconfiguration level, which consists of the set of softwarecomponents that implement system functionality as well as theircontrol and communication interconnections.andP;  This techniqueprovides a clear and flexible way to define, construct, modify andcomprehend a program and is particularly well suited todistributed processing, in which software components may reside ondifferent machines.andP;  The Conic environment developed by theDistributed Systems Group at Imperial College supportsconfiguration programming; it also supports a language forprogramming individual task modules, or processes, withwell-defined interfaces and one for configuring programs fromgroups of task modules.andP;  An example of a patient monitoring systemis used to illustrate the configuration programming conceptsinherent in Conic.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     VisualizationProgram Development TechniquesScientific ResearchTechnologyNew TechniqueSoftware DesignConfigurationDistributed Processing.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The patient module. (chart)Hardware environment. (chart)Initial and extended patient monitoring system. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>